  "prompt": "Why does a player get three or four tennis balls from ball boys and choose two among them for serve?  What is that they look for in selecting the balls to serve?",
  "response": "In tennis, players carefully select tennis balls before serving based on several factors:\n\n1. Fluff and Wear:\n- Players prefer balls with consistent fluff/felt condition\n- They look for balls that have similar wear and feel\n- Newer or less worn balls tend to be preferred for serving\n\n2. Bounce and Condition:\n- Players check the bounce and hardness of the balls\n- They want balls that have similar bounce characteristics\n- Consistent bounce helps in more predictable serving\n\n3. Aerodynamics:\n- Some balls might have slight variations in shape or surface\n- Players choose balls that fly more consistently through the air\n- This helps in controlling serve speed and trajectory\n\n4. Spin Potential:\n- Different ball conditions can affect potential spin\n- Players select balls that provide desired spin characteristics\n\n5. Tournament and Court Conditions:\n- Altitude, humidity, and court surface affect ball behavior\n- Players choose balls that perform best under current conditions\n\nBy selecting two balls that are most consistent and suitable for serving, players aim to maximize their serving performance and control. The additional balls provide options to choose the most appropriate ones for their serving strategy.",
